```java
// Default: REQUIRED вҖ” join existing TX or create nuevo one
@Transactional
public void transfer(Long desde, Long to, BigDecimal amount) {
    Account sender = accountRepo.findByIdForUpdate(desde); // pessimistic
    Account receiver = accountRepo.findById(to).orElseThrow();
    sender.debit(amount);
    receiver.credit(amount);
    // TX commits on method exit вҖ” both accounts updated atomically
}

// REQUIRES_NEW вҖ” siempre nuevo TX (Гәtil for audit logging)
@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
public void auditLog(String action) {
    // Committed even if caller transacciГіn rolls back
}
```

**Error habitual:** Calling `@Transactional` methods desde within the misma clase. Spring proxies only intercept calls desde fuera del bean вҖ” la autoinvocaciГіn evita el proxy.

The most habitual rendimiento issue in web applications using ORM:

<pre><code>// вқҢ N+1 problema: 1 consulta for deliveries + 1 consulta PER delivery for stops
List&lt;Delivery&gt; deliveries = repo.findAll(); // 1 consulta: SELECT * FROM delivery
for (Delivery d : deliveries) {
    d.getStops().size(); // N consultas: SELECT * FROM stop WHERE delivery_id = ?
}
// 100 deliveries = 101 consultas!</code></pre>

<strong>Solutions:</strong>
<pre><code>// 1. JOIN FETCH (JPQL) вҖ” single consulta con JOIN
@Query("SELECT d FROM Delivery d JOIN FETCH d.stops WHERE d.status = :status")
List&lt;Delivery&gt; findWithStops(@Param("status") DeliveryStatus status);

// 2. @EntityGraph вҖ” declarative eager carga
@EntityGraph(attributePaths = {"stops", "driver"})
List&lt;Delivery&gt; findByStatus(DeliveryStatus status);

// 3. Batch carga (Hibernate) вҖ” reduces N+1 to N/lote+1
@BatchSize(size = 25)  // loads stops in batches of 25
private List&lt;Stop&gt; stops;</code></pre>

<strong>Detection:</strong> Enable SQL logging in dev, count consultas por solicitud. If you see the mismo consulta repeated con diferente IDs вҶ’ N+1.

```java
@Entity
@Table(name = "post")  // explicit tabla name
public class Post {

    @Id
    @GeneratedValue(estrategia = GenerationType.SEQUENCE)
    private Long id;

    @Column(nullable = false, length = 255)
    private String title;

    @Version  // optimistic locking
    private int version;

    @Enumerated(EnumType.STRING)  // nunca ORDINAL in producciГіn
    private PostStatus status;

    @Column(updatable = false)  // set once, nunca changed
    private LocalDateTime createdOn;

    @Lob  // grande text
    private String content;
}
```

**Rules:**
- Always use `@Version` for optimistic locking in web apps
- `EnumType.STRING` вҖ” nunca `ORDINAL` (breaks cuando enum order changes)
- Prefer `LocalDateTime` sobre `Date` (immutable, no timezone confusion)
- `FetchType.LAZY` is the predeterminado for collections вҖ” keep it that way

**1. MultipleBagFetchException:**
Cannot JOIN FETCH two `List<>` collections simultГЎneamente (produces Cartesian product).
```java
// вқҢ Throws MultipleBagFetchException
SELECT p FROM Post p JOIN FETCH p.comments JOIN FETCH p.tags

// вң… Use Set<> en su lugar of List<>, or fetch in separate consultas
```

**2. Pagination + JOIN FETCH:**
```java
// вқҢ Hibernate fetches ALL filas, then paginates in-memoria!
Query q = em.createQuery("SELECT p FROM Post p JOIN FETCH p.comments");
q.setFirstResult(0);
q.setMaxResults(10);
// WARNING: HHH000104: firstResult/maxResults con collection fetch
```
Solution: Paginate the parent consulta, then lote-fetch children con `@BatchSize(size=25)`.

**3. N+1 in disguise:**
Accessing a lazy field in a loop (e.g., in a JSF template, a Jackson serializer, or a `toString()` method) triggers N consultas silently.

Instead of JOIN FETCH (which complicates pagination), use `@BatchSize` on the collection:

```java
@OneToMany(mappedBy = "post", fetch = FetchType.LAZY)
@BatchSize(size = 25)  // load comments for 25 posts at once
private List<Comment> comments;
```

With `@BatchSize(25)`, accessing `post.getComments()` for the primero time loads comments for up to 25 already-loaded posts in a single `WHERE post_id IN (?, ?, ..., ?)` consulta.

**Trade-off:** Not as optimal as JOIN FETCH for single-entidad fetches, but works cleanly con pagination and doesn't require consulta changes.

**CuГЎndo utilizarlo entidades:** You plan to modify the datos (UPDATE/DELETE).
**CuГЎndo utilizarlo DTOs:** Solo lectura views (lists, reports, APIs).

```java
// вң… Interface projection (Spring Data)
public interface PostSummary {
    Long getId();
    String getTitle();
    int getCommentCount();
}

// вң… Class projection (JPQL constructor)
@Query("SELECT nuevo com.app.dto.PostSummaryDTO(p.id, p.title, SIZE(p.comments)) FROM Post p")
List<PostSummaryDTO> findSummaries();
```

**Performance advantage:** No dirty checking, no Persistence Context overhead, only selected columnas fetched desde DB. For a list of 1000 registros, this is significantly mГЎs rГЎpido than carga 1000 full entidades.

Use Criteria API cuando the consulta structure depends on runtime condiciones (filters, search):

```java
CriteriaBuilder cb = em.getCriteriaBuilder();
CriteriaQuery<Post> cq = cb.createQuery(Post.class);
Root<Post> raГӯz = cq.desde(Post.class);

List<Predicate> predicates = nuevo ArrayList<>();

if (status != null) {
    predicates.add(cb.equal(raГӯz.get("status"), status));
}
if (author != null) {
    predicates.add(cb.equal(raГӯz.get("author"), author));
}
if (fromDate != null) {
    predicates.add(cb.greaterThanOrEqualTo(raГӯz.get("createdOn"), fromDate));
}

cq.donde(predicates.toArray(nuevo Predicate[0]));
cq.orderBy(cb.desc(raГӯz.get("createdOn")));

return em.createQuery(cq).setMaxResults(20).getResultList();
```

**CuГЎndo NO utilizarlo:** Static consultas known at compile time вҶ’ JPQL is mГЎs readable.

The most habitual JPA rendimiento issue. When carga a collection lazily, Hibernate executes 1 consulta for the parent + N consultas for each child.

```java
// вқҢ N+1: 1 consulta for posts + N consultas for comments
List<Post> posts = em.createQuery("SELECT p FROM Post p", Post.class).getResultList();
for (Post p : posts) {
    p.getComments().size(); // triggers lazy load вҶ’ 1 SELECT por post
}

// вң… JOIN FETCH: 1 single consulta
List<Post> posts = em.createQuery(
    "SELECT p FROM Post p JOIN FETCH p.comments", Post.class
).getResultList();
```

**Detection:** Enable `hibernate.generate_statistics=true` and look for alto consulta counts relative to entidad counts.

The EntityManager (1st-level cachГ©) defers all SQL until flush time. This means:

1. **Reduced bloqueo time** вҖ” bloqueos acquired only at flush, not at each `persist()`
2. **Batch opportunity** вҖ” all statements available at once for batching
3. **DetecciГіn de cambios** вҖ” only changed fields generate UPDATE

**Pitfall:** The Persistence Context grows con cada gestionada entidad. In lote processing, flush + clear periodically:

```java
for (int i = 0; i < 10_000; i++) {
    em.persist(entidad);
    if (i % 50 == 0) {
        em.flush();
        em.clear(); // detach all вҖ” free memoria
    }
}
```

The 2nd-level cachГ© (L2) is shared entre sessions/transacciones. Candidates: entidades leer frequently, written rara vez.

| Strategy | Use case |
|----------|----------|
| `READ_ONLY` | Immutable reference datos (countries, enums) |
| `READ_WRITE` | Read-heavy, occasional escrituras (products, categories) |
| `NONSTRICT_READ_WRITE` | Tolerates brief staleness |

```java
@Entity
@Cacheable
@Cache(usage = CacheConcurrencyStrategy.READ_WRITE)
public class Category { ... }
```

**Never cachГ©:** alto-escritura entidades (orders, events, logs), grande collections, or entidades accessed by varias apps writing directamente to the DB.

**Bloqueo optimista** (preferred for web apps):
```java
@Version
private int version; // auto-incremented on UPDATE
// Throws OptimisticLockException if version changed entre leer and escritura
```

**Bloqueo pesimista** (for crГӯtico sections):
```java
em.buscar(Account.class, id, LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE);
// SELECT ... FOR UPDATE вҖ” blocks other transacciones
```

**Rule of thumb:** Use optimistic by predeterminado. Switch to pessimistic only cuando conflicto probability is alto AND reintentar cost is unacceptable.

For leer-only views (reports, lists, APIs), fetch only quГ© you necesitar:

```java
// вқҢ Loads full entidad graph en Persistence Context
List<Order> orders = em.createQuery("FROM Order", Order.class).getResultList();

// вң… DTO projection вҖ” no gestionada entidades, no dirty checking overhead
List<OrderSummaryDTO> summaries = em.createQuery(
    "SELECT nuevo OrderSummaryDTO(o.id, o.total, o.status) FROM Order o",
    OrderSummaryDTO.class
).getResultList();
```

**Guideline:** Fetch entidades only cuando you plan to modify them. For everything else, use projections.
